"1332–1370","1336–Female":"1336–Deceased","1352–1378":"1352–1378","1361–1400":"1361–1400","1280–1332":"1280–1332","1304–Female":"1304–Deceased","1352":"1352","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","1336":"1336","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1331":"1331","Englefield, Berkshire, England":"Englefield, Berkshire, England",", Devon, , England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Alwington, Devon, England":"Alwington, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Alwington, Devonshire, England":"Alwington, Devon, England","Devon, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Coffin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southwestern England, of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Middle English <i>cofin</i>, <i>coffin</i>, Old French <i>cof(f)in</i> (from Late Latin <i>cophinus</i>, Greek <i>kophinos</i>) ‘container, basket; coffer, chest (for keeping treasures, documents, armour, etc.)’. Early bearers of this as a hereditary surname were of knightly rank. Old French <i>cofin</i> was synonymous with <i>coffer</i>, and it may be that <i>Cofin</i> was used to denote a keeper of the (royal) coffer, attested in Anglo-Latin <i>cofferarius</i>. Compare   Coffer  . The modern English word <i>coffin</i> is a specialized development of this term, not attested until the 16th century.","History: Tristram Coffin came from Brixham, Devon, to Haverhill, MA, before 1647. An important line of his descendants is associated with Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard."],"variants":[{"name":"Coffer","meanings":["English: metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>cofre</i>, <i>coffre</i>, <i>coffer</i> ‘box, chest’ (from Old French <i>cof(f)rehere</i>), used to denote a box or coffer maker (Old French <i>coffrier</i>), perhaps also for a treasurer.","Probably also an Americanized form of German   Kaufer   or <b>Kauffer</b>."]},{"name":"Coffing","meanings":["English: variant of   Coffin  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":5,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When David Coffin I was born in 1332, in Alwington, Devon, England, his father, John Coffin I, was 52 and his mother, Isabella, was 28. He married Thomasine of Alwington in 1360, in Alwington, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1370, in his hometown, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1332–1370":"1332–1370","1336–Female":"1336–Surnud","1352–1378":"1352–1378","1361–1400":"1361–1400","1280–1332":"1280–1332","1304–Female":"1304–Surnud","1352":"1352","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","1336":"1336","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","13